A?The Worst-Case weather conditions which were used for this scenario are uncommon;

A?Industry and ASME standards were followed for the manufacture and quality control of the High Pressure Ammonia Receiver.  U-1A manufacturerA?s data reports and State Permit will be on file the facility;

A?The High Pressure Receiver is located inside the Engine Room and cannot be impacted by a vehicle.  The Engine Room is kept locked and cannot be accessed except by authorized personnel;

A?Ammonia is not corrosive in this service and the High Pressure Receiver will be maintained in good condition and inspected at least annually by the personnel and every 4 years by the insurance carrier or by the State;

A?Dual safety relief valves limit operating pressure in the High Pressure Receiver; and

A?The facility will have a training program designed to ensure that the system is operated by experienced and qualified personnel.



Several alternative (more likely) release scenarios at the facility involve the following:



A?Release of 504 pounds over a period of 8 hours due to a A?pinA? hole in a pipe on the roof.  The ammonia lines will be painted or insulated to prevent rusting or corrosion and inspected annually.

A?Release of 1090 pounds over a period of 60 minutes due to a flange gasket leaking at one of the connections at a solenoid valve or strainer located on the roof.

A?Release of 138 pounds over a one minute period due to the rupture of the ammonia receiving hose during the a charging of the system.



None of the above alternate scenarios would pose a hazard to the public at a distance of more than .1 miles.



The likelihood of an alternative release scenario is minimized for the following reasons:



